headline: DraftKings Sacked By NFL Bets, Enters Prediction Markets
summary: DraftKings said Thursday it would launch a prediction market for sports outcomes in coming months, potentially turning a competitive threat into a growth opportunity.  DraftKings CEO Jason Robins said in a letter to shareholders that "just a handful of NFL games had a pronounced effect" on revenue, with a hit of more than $300 million in September and October.  Although DraftKings cut its full-year outlook, Robins said he is "the most bullish" he has ever been about the company's future, citing accelerating "underlying growth," new exclusive marketing agreements with ESPN and NBCUniversal, and the launch of sports prediction contracts.

After cutting its full-year outlook amid bettor-friendly sports outcomes, DKNG stock fell to a two-year low early Friday before turning higher.  DraftKings CEO Jason Robins said in a letter to shareholders that "just a handful of NFL games had a pronounced effect" on revenue, with a hit of more than $300 million in September and October.
